==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*augan-'' ‘eye’, from Indo-European ''*h₃ekʷ-'' ‘eye, to see’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[age|āge]], Old High German [[ouga]] (German [[Auge]]), Old Franconian [[oga|ōga]], Old Saxon [[oga|ōga]] (Dutch [[oog]]), Old Norse [[auga]] (Swedish [[öga]], Danish [[øje]]), Gothic [[𐌰𐌿𐌲𐍉]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Greek [[ὄσσε]] ‘eye’, Latin [[oculus]] ‘eye’, Avestan ''aši'' ‘the eyes’, Old Church Slavonic [[око]] (Polish [[oko]]), Armenian [[աչք]], Old Irish [[enech]], Tocharian A ''ak''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'æ:aje/

===Noun===
'''ēaġe''' ''n'' (Plural: '''ēaġan''')
#an [[eye]]
#:''Eagum to wynne'': to their eyes' delight.  (''Exeter Book'')

